SIMPLE: finch
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Finch
<hw>Finch</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧nch)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Finches</plw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧nch"⟦ecr⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[AS.
<ets>finc</ets>; akin to D. <ets>vink</ets>, OHG. <ets>fincho</ets>, G.
<ets>fink</ets>; cf. W. <ets>pinc</ets> a finch; also E.
<ets>spink</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A small singing bird of
many genera and species, belonging to the family
<fam>Fringillid⟦ae⟧</fam>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The word is often used in composition, as in
chaf<xex>finch</xex>, gold<xex>finch</xex>, grass<xex>finch</xex>,
pine<xex>finch</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bramble finch</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Brambling</er>.</cd>
-- <col><b>Canary finch</b></col>, <cd>the canary bird.</cd> --
<col><b>Copper finch</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Chaffinch</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Diamond finch</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>Diamond</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Finch falcon</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>one of several
very small East Indian falcons of the genus <gen>Hierax</gen>.</cd> --
<col><b>To pull a finch</b></col>, <cd>to swindle an ignorant or
unsuspecting person.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Privily a
<xex>finch</xex> eke could he <xex>pull</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Finchbacked</ent>⟦br⟧
